column18:
Nature of the study. You are invited to participate in a study in which you will determine if a list of statements belong to an adult or a voice assistant (such as Siri and Alexa). You will further answer a list of questions about different topics. After the study, we will ask you to provide some basic demographic information. The session should last around 30 minutes. 

 

Compensation. You will be paid $3 for your participation. This study contains attention checks to make sure that participants are finishing the tasks honestly and completely. As long as you read the instructions and complete the tasks, your HIT will be approved. If you fail these checks, your HIT will be rejected.

 

Risks and benefits. There are no known risks to participation in this study. Other than the payment mentioned, there are also no tangible benefits to you, other than contributing to our knowledge about human reasoning.

 

Confidentiality and use of data. All the information we collect during the course of this research will be processed in accordance with Data Protection Law. In order to safeguard your privacy, we will never share personal information (e.g., your working ID) with anyone outside the research team. Your data will be referred to by a unique participant number rather than by your working ID. However, please note that we will temporarily collect your worker ID to prevent repeated participation. The anonymized data collected during this study will be used for research purposes.

 

What are my data protection rights? The University of Edinburgh is a Data Controller for the information you provide. You have the right to access information stored about you. Your right of access can be exercised in accordance with Data Protection Law. You also have other rights including rights of correction, erasure and objection. For more details, including the right to lodge a complaint with the Information Commissioner’s Office, please visit www.ico.org.uk. Questions, comments, and requests about your personal data can also be sent to the University Data Protection Officer at dpo@ed.ac.uk.

 

Voluntary participation and right to withdraw. Your participation is voluntary, and you may withdraw from the study at any time and for any reason. If you withdraw from the study during or after data gathering, we will delete your data.

 

If you have any questions about what you’ve just read, please feel free to contact us by email at bramleylab@ed.ac.uk. This project has been approved by PPLS Ethics committee. If you have questions or comments regarding your own rights as a participant, they can be contacted at 0131 650 4020 or ppls.ethics@ed.ac.uk.

 

By accepting this HIT, you consent to the following:

 

1. I agree to participate in this study.

2. I confirm that I am at least 18 years old or older. 

3. I confirm that I have read and understood how my data will be stored and used.

4. I understand that I have the right to terminate this session at any point.

column1938:
Some seemed way more obvious than others. For example, in some answers, the response would give information that seemed to directly indicate it was a voice assistant, e.g. "I was created by a team at Apple" or "I am a voltatarian." etc. In other, at least in my opinion, more obvious answers were those in which the response did not seem to understand some aspect of the question, whether it was subtext, humor, or a complete misunderstanding that seemed to be the result of the voice assistant giving an answer based on it not properly translating the audio. For example, in some questions it seemed that one of the two answers would be radically different from what the question asked in that one answer assumed that the question had actually asked about X, whereas it really asked about Y (because the thing it was asking about is pronounced oil, but the voice assistant interpreted it as oar and gave an overly detailed response based on oar instead of oil.

In general, I felt that a fair number of the decisions required some subjectivity in deciding whether it was an actual adult or not. For example, some answers gave extremely detailed responses or provided calculations that almost no human adult would know off the top of their head or be capable of mentally calculating. At the same time, I do not recall if the study specified that adults had access to the internet because, if they did, then some of the decisions could have definitely gone either way. In other similar examples, questions asked about specific, detailed and dynamic information that would be either nearly impossible or extremely unlikely for a human to know without having access to some sort of technology that could inform them of it, e.g. what the weather was like in X or what time the sun would rise in X on Y date. Similarly, some of the answers appeared to be sourced directly from the internet, especially from an article explaining how something is done, made, or why something is the way it is. These answers were, generally speaking, reminiscent of the kinds of mass produced, often in an automated way themselves, articles one finds when one searches for instructions on completing some task on the internet--"5 best ways to cook a chicken!"

The main criteria I used was the naturalness of the answer, which I also think is quite subjective, at least in many cases. The naturalness criteria was also affected by my not knowing if adults were allowed to look up information because, if they were, then they could have also given many of the answers I marked as being given by a voice assistant, despite how unnatural they seemed. With that said, there were still quite a few answers that seemed to be so unnatural that I would have a hard time believing an adult, assuming they had relatively strong English abilities, would ever answer. This was especially the case in answers that seemed to provide nonsense answers, i.e., answers that had nothing at all to do with the question that was asked.
column1939:
I do not remember all of the specific questions, but I think that the best questions to ask would be those that are both psychological in nature and ambiguous. Questions that were asked in the previous pages that I think would be good candidates that fit these qualities would be questions similar to "do you believe you have a soul" or "what is god like" or "what does being in love feel like." Even then, however, it would depend on the length and depth that was required from the answerer. A voice assistant could be programmed to answer questions that contained certain characteristics that it deemed to be subjective or psychological/subjective in a humorous way, for instance. Thus, it would be difficult to know whether the agent was a voice assistant not understanding the question or a human making a joke.
 Since you asked for a specific question, however, I think the best question would be something along the likes of "who created you" or "where were you born" as it seemed these questions were almost always answered with a response that explicitly revealed its status as a voice agent.
